<div id="p11" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#2&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=11#p11">15-Oct-2007,Mon 13:12:19</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=3">higopi</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Expert Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"><img src="img/avatars/3.jpg" width="60" height="60" alt="" /></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Regarding Indian Scripts in Java Web Application</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>Hi Vijay<br /><br />To make the Java application to display the Telugu Unicode you need to attach a Telugu font along with your JAR and load that font in the component you want to display.<br /><br />For eg.<br /></p><div class="codebox"><div class="incqbox"><h4>Code:</h4><div class="scrollbox" style="height: 7.5em"><pre>JTextArea editorbox = new JTextArea();
editorbox.setFont(Font.createFont(Font.TRUETYPE_FONT,
this.getClass().getResourceAsStream(&quot;/fonts/gautami.ttf&quot;)).deriveFont(Font.PLAIN,12));</pre></div></div></div><p>The above code will load the Gautami font from the /fonts directory in the JAR file and display the Telugu text in the above defined editorbox correctly. Hence you need to put the gautami.ttf font under the /fonts directory within your JAR file. Gautami font is supplied with Windows XP and Office XP.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="postsignature"><hr />Thanks,<br /><br />Gopi<br />Pick any two of &quot;Quality, Quick, Cheap&quot; service from me.</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
